\fs36 \cf2 The series structure question is really a marketing funnel question\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 When you ask "is the stuff we have strong enough for series?" \'97 the answer depends on what kind of series you're building. There are three models that work in self-help audio:\
Model A \'97 The Encyclopedia Series. Each installment covers a distinct subtopic comprehensively. ("Anxiety Decoded: Social Anxiety," "Anxiety Decoded: Panic Attacks," etc.) This is what your dev's plan assumes. It works but requires 6+ books before the series feels complete, and each book needs to stand alone.\
Model B \'97 The Progressive Journey Series. Installments build on each other. Book 1 is foundations/awareness, Book 2 is tools/techniques, Book 3 is real-world application, Book 4 is maintenance/relapse prevention. This is much easier to market because each book creates demand for the next. Your arc system is actually perfect for this \'97 you'd use different arcs per installment rather than different topics.\
Model C \'97 The Persona Series. Same core anxiety content, repackaged for different personas. "Anxiety for Healthcare Workers," "Anxiety for New Parents," "Anxiety for Executives." This is where Phoenix's persona engine gives you a massive structural advantage \'97 and it's the hardest model for competitors to replicate.\
My recommendation: combine B and C. Build a 4-book progressive journey as the anchor, then use persona variants to multiply the catalog without thematic collapse. Your anti-cluster system handles the rest.\
